                            <div class="container">
                    <div class="exc-container">
                        <div class="muscle-text bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                            <h3><strong>Latissimus Dorsi</strong></h3><p>The <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448120/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">latissimus dorsi</a> is a large, triangular-shaped muscle group that spans most of the upper back. Its primary functions include shoulder adduction and extension. This means bringing the arms closer to the bodyâ€™s midline and behind.</p><p>When bringing an object or weight down or back, your latissimus dorsi muscles are likely the primary movers. They function to extend your arms as you bring the barbell behind your head. They slightly adduct the shoulders to bring them into the midline as you bring the barbell to the starting position.</p><p>In the barbell pullover, the latissimus dorsi muscles show an electric activity of <a href="https://www.researchgate.net/publication/263449260_Comparison_of_electromyographic_activity_during_the_bench_press_and_barbell_pullover_exercises" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">approximately 60 uV</a>. This is linearly related to a muscle contraction, meaning the stronger the contraction the higher the uV reading. </p>                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
